Based on this spike https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/348282 we propose to add the fields captured in the schema below to the `PipelineSecurityReportFinding`:

```graphql
  extend type PipelineSecurityReportFinding {
    descriptionHtml: String!
  }
```

This will make sure that the GraphQL API returns all the data that is currently showing within the pipeline finding's modal.

### Implementation Plan

- [x] ~backend Add `description_html` to `PipelineSecurityReportFinding`
  - Use https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/master/ee/app/graphql/types/vulnerability_type.rb as an example.


### Verification

To verify this issue, use a GraphQL query to confirm that the `descriptionHtml` field is available:

```
query {
  project(fullPath:"<project path>") {
    pipeline(iid:"<pipeline iid>") {
      securityReportFindings(first:1) {
        nodes {
          reportType
          descriptionHtml
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

#### Summary

In the current implementation, we have the following to track projects and wikis replication and verification:

1. We have 1 row in the `project_repository_state` table in the main database to track project and wiki verification
2. We have 1 row in the `project_registry` table in the tracking database to handle project and wiki replication and synchronization.

As part of https://gitlab.com/groups/gitlab-org/-/epics/4623, we need to separate projects and wikis in their tables.

#### Proposal

1. [Extract wiki replication and verification data in its own table](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/367928):
    1. Create the table `wiki_repository_state` to track the verification state for wiki repositories;
    1. Make the legacy code responsible to verify wikis to maintain both wiki tables `project_repository_state` and `wiki_repository_state` simultaneously until %16.0 behind a feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`;
    1. Create the registry table `wiki_repository_registry ` to track replication and verification state for wiki repositories;
    1. Make the legacy code responsible for replicating/verifying wikis to maintain both wiki tables `project_registry` and `wiki_repository_registry` simultaneously until %16.0 behind a feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`;
    1. Change the metrics gathering implementation to support both tables behind a feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`;
    1. Enable the `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration` feature flag;


1. [Migrate wikis replication/verification to use SSF](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/367925)
    1. Make the SSF code responsible to verify wikis to maintain both wiki tables `project_repository_state` and `wiki_repository_state` simultaneously until %16.0 behind a feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`;
    1. Make the SSF code responsible for replicating/verifying wikis to maintain both wiki tables `project_registry` and `wiki_repository_registry ` simultaneously until %16.0 behind a feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`; 

1. [Migrate projects replication/verification to use SSF](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/367926)

1. Warning about updating to %16.0 if there is any remaining unmigrated data
    1. Create a rake task to check if there is any remaining unmigrated data;
    1. Create a rake task to migrate any remaining unmigrated data;
    1. Update the [version-specific upgrade docs](https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/administration/geo/replication/version_specific_upgrades.html), to tell customers to check if there is any remaining unmigrated data or run the rake task to migrate the data, otherwise, unmigrated wikis will be resynced after upgrade to version %16.0;

1. Remove projects and wikis migration code in %16.1
    1. Remove the feature flag `geo_project_wikis_ssf_migration`;
    1. Remove wiki columns in the `project_repository_state` table; 
    1. Remove wiki columns in the `project_registry` table;
    1. Remove the legacy code responsible for replicating/verifying project and wiki repositories;

Related to https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/merge_requests/92056#note_1023017885

When user adds child in hierarchy widget and searches work items in the dropdown, we use generic work item/issue search which searches for text in title and description and this search is done only by full words. We should consider if we should add support for searching only in titles by any substring.

---
### Tasks

- [x] ~backend Expose this `in` parameter in GraphQL API (among other filtering arguments in [`WorkItemsResolver`](https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/blob/master/app/graphql/resolvers/work_items_resolver.rb))

    This task is now complete so we can specify which field to search on when querying for work items.
    <details><summary>Example query</summary>

    ```graphql
    query searchWorkItems {
      project(fullPath: "gitlab-org/gitlab-test") {
        workItems(search: "another", in: DESCRIPTION) {
          edges {
            node {
              title
              description
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }

    ```

    </details>

    The options for the `in` param are `DESCRIPTION`, `TITLE` and `[DESCRIPTION, TITLE]`. If not specified, it searches in title and description by default. 
- [ ] ~frontend Pass the new parameter to the query - FE being addressed in https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/issues/368757

